<font color="#FF0000">HERE WE GO AGAIN!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Nov  9 10:58:55 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Hopefully this thread will not drift off into another display of contempt for dysfunctional people who come here to antagonize hurting veterans.<br>
I have always wondered why people write gross messages on bathroom walls.  It seems a weird way of expressing oneself.. and plays hell with the paint job.<br>
Is that what is happening here?  Seems that way!  Foul language.. stupid statements.. redundant theme.<br>
You don't get your laundry clean by washing it in a dirty toilet... and we as a population of traumatized veterans have a lot of cleaning up to do.<br>
Not only are there a lot of hurting veterans but these same folks are passing their pain on to wives, friends and kids.. and the veteran ends up adding more pain to his mountain of despair.  In today's Neanderthal style of viewing PTSD most victims are viewed with distain rather than an empathtic perspective of &quot;Can I help.&quot;  As we sink deeper into this black quarmire of anger, sorrow and hopelessness we are confirming to the unappreciative world the false premiss that..&quot;those Vietnam Vets are a bunch of cry babies!&quot;  Of course these perspectives come from those who did not experience what we did..saw and smelled.  Much of the care given today's veteran is from the Veterans Administration, an agency who's primary mission is to reduce the budget at all costs...even the welfare of shattered men and women.<br>
All that is left is for veterans to drag their buddies from the battlefields of the mind and administer the one healing drug that we have..that feeling of acceptance and understanding.. conveyed in &quot;Welcome Home.&quot;  With or without the help of a few mental health professionals who do care, the loved ones whom we have not yet alienated, and concerned patriots.. we are left alone to care for our own.  Not Bad..considering the fact that we have some pretty smart brothers among us who are generous with their words and their hearts.<br>
Cursing the fox who killed the chickens is going to get us nowhere!  We can't exterminate all the foxes, either!  But we CAN save what we have left and improve the chicken house.<br>
Of all the problems we have been blessed with..shabby interpersonal relationship skills head the list.  Every adverse thing that affects us seems to culminate in our inability to get along with others...rage, mistrust, intrusive horror, a sense of being used and violated, etc., seems to disengage our &quot;smarts&quot; when we begin to shout our confused feelings to an unsympathetic world.  Instead of gaining support..we drive people from us.<br>
I for one am disgusted with one particular individual, Barry C. Spatz.  Like some drunken heckler at the town hall meeting, he appears, not to contribute to the achievers but to drag everyone down to his low station in life.  He represents everything counterproductive to a clean, wholesome, safe democracy.  Rebellion is a tool to be used when things are going wrong.. it is not a tool of convience to be used when someone does not want to face responsibility.  My child has the right to rebel against that which would threaten or deprive her of liberty at home or outside the home.  But she is not allowed to use the tool of rebellion when she is asked to carry out the trash or wash the dinner dishes.  One should use good judgement when wielding this important and necessary, but dangerous tool.<br>
I propose that we start here and search for ways to heal ourselves and one another.<br>
I can no longer devote all my time to hunting a mangey cur, while my surviving chickens starve to death.  I must focus on salvaging what is left.. for me and my brothers of choice.<br><br>
Mustang Two Four
